Sleep spindle modulation by transcranial temporal interference (TI) stimulation
================================================================================

Overview
--------
This dataset contains scalp EEG recordings from 20 healthy young adults (sub-05
to sub-24) who took a single afternoon nap while receiving counterbalanced
blocks of transcranial temporal interference (TI) stimulation. Three conditions
were delivered in counterbalanced order: a 5 Hz envelope frequency, a 1 Hz
envelope frequency, and a Sham (OFF) control. The primary aim of the study is
to characterise condition-dependent modulation of sleep spindle properties.

Five additional participants who did not achieve stable N2 or N3 sleep during
the nap were excluded prior to publication and are not included in this
dataset. The recorder-side numbering ran from sub-P005 to sub-P024 and has
been remapped here to sub-05 to sub-24 for clarity. Earlier recorder IDs
(sub-P001 to sub-P004) correspond to pilot participants and are not shipped.

Acquisition
-----------
- System: Brain Products actiCHamp (S/N 20110416), 32-channel scalp EEG.
- Cap: EasyCap M1 layout, 10-20 placement.
- Sampling: 10 kHz (downsampled to 500 Hz in derivatives; 256 Hz EDF available
  on request for sleep staging).
- Acquisition reference: FCz. Acquisition ground: AFz.
- Two scalp channels were excluded due to a connector-position mismatch with
  the EasyCap montage, yielding 30 usable EEG electrodes.
- EOG: two electrodes placed 1 cm lateral and 1 cm superior to the outer
  canthi, each referenced to the contralateral mastoid (LOC -> right mastoid,
  ROC -> left mastoid). EMG: single submental chin electrode.
- Stimulator: TI Solutions AG, TIBS-R V3.0.
- TI electrodes: 1.5 cm round rubber pads, Ten20 conductive paste. Frontal
  pair F7-F8; parietal pair P5-P6 (P5 and P6 do not coincide with EEG sites).
- Active stimulation conditions:
    * 1 Hz envelope: pair 1 at 2000 Hz, pair 2 at 2001 Hz, 2 mA zero-to-peak
      per pair.
    * 5 Hz envelope: pair 1 at 2000 Hz, pair 2 at 2005 Hz, 2 mA zero-to-peak
      per pair.
- Sham (OFF) condition: both channel pairs at 0 Hz and 0 mA. Stimulation
  was fully ramped down during OFF blocks; no carrier was active.
- Linear 5 s ramps (at the prevailing carrier frequency) preceded and
  followed every transition that changed stimulation parameters.
- Trial structure: 8 s per trial, 5 trials per condition block, 40 s blocks,
  continuous block sequence for the duration of the nap.
- Synchronisation: EEG and stimulation markers were synchronised via Lab
  Streaming Layer (LSL).
- Setting: Surrey Sleep Research Centre, single daytime session starting
  approximately 14:00.

Events
------
Events were recovered from the LSL StimMarkers stream and stored in each
subject's _events.tsv. Trial-level markers encode condition, block index, and
within-block trial index (e.g. '5HZ_001_003' is the third trial of block 1
in the 5 Hz condition). Ramp segments carry the stim_phase 'rampingUp' or
'rampingDown' and refractory segments adjacent to ramps carry 'refract'.
Two boundary markers, STIM_START and STIM_STOP, delimit the overall
stimulation period.

Derivatives
-----------
The directory derivatives/ contains analysis-ready outputs:
- spindlepilot-preprocessing: epoched FieldTrip MAT files at 500 Hz after the
  preprocessing pipeline described in the associated analysis repository.
- comprehensive-analysis: comprehensive_analysis.mat (event tables, sleep
  stage assignments, trial metadata) and the YASA spindle / slow-wave / sleep
  stage CSV outputs consumed by the figure scripts.

Large pre-computed time-frequency representations (~25 GB) are not included
here; they live in a separate archive linked from the analysis repository.

Code
----
All analysis and conversion code is published at
https://github.com/TobiasRaufeisen/Spindle-TI

Ethics and compensation
-----------------------
The study was approved by the University of Surrey Ethics Committee
(FHMS 22-23 123 EGA / ERM 873). Participants received compensation of GBP 40
plus travel expenses up to GBP 20.

